commit.message:
Merge branch 'appveyor': enable window CI

closes #9
add windows-build.cmd script
enable appveyor (windows CI testing)
update NEWS for 0.8 release
include spake2.parameters when building the dist/sdist
upgrade to versioneer-0.18
update docs to describe the new parameters layout
fix 'tox -e speed' to work with the new parameters/ layout
drop py2.6 support, make it clear that py3.6 is supported
tox.ini: set usedevelop=True for faster tests

move parameters into separately importable modules, for speed

Computing the "arbitrary elements" for the integer groups was adding 400ms to
magic-wormhole's import time on my laptop, which is a lot for groups that it
doesn't use.

This is a compatibility break for any application that uses non-default
parameters (i.e. "from spake2 import Params1024"). Such apps need to be
changed to use "from spake2.parameters.i1024 import Params1024".
setup.py: update github URL
add py3.6 to the tox/travis config
fix py2-ism in test vector
test_compat: add some vectors for internal scalars
Merge branch 'pr8' (early part)
Update README.md
add hkdf as dependency and correct PyPy2
update NEWS for 0.7 release
setup.cfg: make universal (py2+py3) wheels
MANIFEST.in: include tox.ini
minor comment fix
improve test coverage: catch errors in Symmetric
ignore coverage.xml

ed25519: comment out unused password_to_scalar()

We now use the HKDF approach for all groups, including ed25519.

change final hash function (COMPATIBILITY BREAK)

This modifies the finalization function (which hashes the transcript and
shared group element into the final key) to match the proposal in
https://github.com/bitwiseshiftleft/sjcl/pull/273 . As with the previous
compatibility-breaking patches, applications which use this revision of
the SPAKE2 library will not be able to communicate with those using the
previous version.

merge finalize.py back into spake2.py

It needs to be a separate function, but doesn't need to live in a
separate file.

Merge branch 'hkdf' (COMPATIBILITY BREAK)

This changes password_to_scalar() and arbitrary_element() to a new
derivation function, using HKDF and matching the proposed functions in
https://github.com/bitwiseshiftleft/sjcl/pull/273 . Users of this
library from after this commit will not interoperate with those who use
the library from before this commit: they will get "WrongPasswordError"
all the time.

closes #5 (rebased the original commits)

add HKDF test vectors

This uses the SHA256 test vectors from RFC5869, and a copy of hkdf.py
that I wrote a couple years ago, for comparison.

drop pypy3 compatibility

pypy3 currently implements the equivalent of Python-3.2.5, and we only
support Python-3.3 or higher. This wasn't a problem before, but we now
depend on HKDF (from PyPI), and it uses bytearrays and buffers in a way
that fails on pypy3 (and presumably Python-3.2).
